SIMPLE: persecute
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Persecute
<hw>Per"se*cute</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Persecuted</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Persecuting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>pers⟦eacute⟧cueter</ets>, L. <ets>persequi</ets>, <ets>persecutus</ets>, to pursue, prosecute; <ets>per + sequi</ets> to follow, pursue. See <er>Per-</er>, and <er>Second</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pursue in a manner to injure, grieve, or afflict; to beset with cruelty or malignity; to harass; especially, to afflict, harass, punish, or put to death, for adherence to a particular religious creed or mode of worship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Do good to them that hate you, and pray for them which despitefully use you, and <qex>persecute</qex> you.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. v. 44.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To harass with importunity; to pursue with persistent solicitations; to annoy.</def>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To oppress; harass; distress; worry; annoy.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>persecuted</ent>⟦br⟧
